n of the plaintiff's power and suggests that mediation as an approach to conflict resolution is structured to favor powerful--often corporate--interests.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aDroit et anthropologie. 0aLaw and anthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aamerican democracy.  aanthropology.  abusiness corporations.  acivic.  acorporate interests.  ademocracy.  adispute resolution.  aeconomic justice.  aglobalization.  alawyers.  alegal anthropologists.  alegal anthropology.  alegal history.  alegal issues.  alegislation.  amediation.  amodern law.  aneoliberal ideology.  aplaintiffs role.  apolitical activists.  apower of the law.  arole of the law.  asocial activists.  asocial change.  asocial justice.  asocial science.  aunited states.  aus judicial system.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093618840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520936188423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520936188/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles